flowRoot.flowPara: The tracking provides an event by event estimate of the rotational location of the camera. For this, a basic particle filter with a constant position motion model is used. I.e. we assume the camera doesn't move in any directed way.
Bayes rule is used to update the weight of a particle according to:
Here, z is the measured contrast between the current and the previous point in the map:

Where M(p) is the intensity of the scene im-age (the map) at point p. The likelihood of the absolute log intensity difference (contrast) z given a hypothesis of the current camera position Rit, is simply a gaussian centered around a known contrast which likely generates an event.
Particles are resampled whenever the sum of squared weights is over 2/N.
possible improvements: use more complex motion model (constant velocity or acceleration).

An event camera is a silicon retina which outputs not a sequence of video frames like a standard camera, but a stream of asynchronous spikes, each with pixel location, sign and precise timing, indicating when individual pixels record a threshold log intensity change.
While this vastly reduces the bitrate by eliminating redundant information, offers very high dynamic range and temporal resolution, no full image is ever transmitted.
Here, we show a method for reconstructing a full mosaic of a scene without any additional sensing by jointly tracking the rotation of the camera and estimating scene gradients.

Integrating up the events into a full image is trivial when you already know the exact trajectory of the camera. Conversly, it is easy to track the camera movement when the scene image (the map) is already known. This presents us with a circular dependency (also known as a chicken-and-egg problem). As it turns out however, just running with it converges relatively quickly to a stable solution.

To calibrate the camera intrinsics and extrinsics, a simple checkerboard is normally used. However, a static scene would not provide any data from the DVS, so we display the pattern on a screen and let it flicker very quickly. Standard camera calibration toolboxes can the employed.
